gm, after my personal audit of sn116 contract and finding 3 ways the funds can be frozen by the owner and 1 way funds can be rugged, I decided to check this contract too.

in short, yes all of the funds in this contract can be rugged by the owner at any time. Why? The contract is UUPS‑upgradeable by onlyOwner. This means the owner can update the logic to have all the funds transferred out to his coldkey then just upgrade the proxy to it. Specifically, this function: https://github.com/Tenexium/tenex-subnet/blob/1c93d78e2b9fa85b261d82d44954ebb3e1f588e2/contracts/core/TenexiumProtocol.sol#L766

The owner to rug, would just need to call upgradeToAndCall which changes the code and then invokes _authorizeUpgrade and can immediately call a function on the new implementation. It could be a transferall for the entire balance in the pool. 

This also defeats the point of the taostats verification because all of the logic in the contract can change at any time without any notice yet the contract would still show as "verified" on taostats.

fyi we had this same concern with subnet 51 contract. Although it makes it much easier to make any changes to your contract, it's obviously better for security. So although it's a longer process, the correct way to upgrade should be:

1. make whatever changes you need to make to the code
2. deploy a new contract
3. miners/lps have to withdraw from this contract and deposit to the new one.
please be careful when depositing funds to things like this

btw we (the moderators) also banned one of the sn67 developers from bittensor discord for being part of an organized scammer group.

Registration costs 0.1 TAO, the funds will be withdrawn from your coldkey wallet. If you do it via the command line you will need to edit the .env file with your keys. More info on how to get the keys is available in the Miner documentation section on GitHub. If you go through the website, you can do the equivalents of associate and addliq steps. You still need to register via btcli.

Of course, we read the instructions, but they're not very clear, and we're afraid of messing up the settings that were already working.
And since there aren't any instructions that are understandable to most people, there aren't many people online.

The website leverages the Bittensor EVM. Miner registration is done on Bittensor itself, as specified in https://docs.learnbittensor.org/miners. Instructions how to edit the env file are here https://github.com/Tenexium/tenex-subnet?tab=readme-ov-file#for-miners-liquidity-providers, with detailed explanation how to get the your MetaMask H160 private key and the second link provides you with a website where if you enter your hotkey SS58 address it will give you the public key you need (or you can get that key via btcli, if that’s how you manage your wallet). With those two pieces of info, you should be able to edit the env file accordingly if you go via the command line route for associating and then adding liquidity. If you go the website route, you will already be connected with your H160 address and the only thing you need to do before adding liquidity is to provide your hotkey SS58 address which should be registered via btcli. Hope this helps.
